in my motherhood era.
my peaceful era.
my quiet era.
my private era.
my happiest era.
my soft era.

Word was everyone hates the newborn stage and I haven’t been able to wrap my head around why? I love it. Every single thing about it. Our days are calm, slow, full of snuggles, and our nights have been restful. We get to watch him change, grow, and develop his own personality every day. 

Life before motherhood I was so quick to wish away time, always anxiously awaiting what was coming next. But now I find myself so deeply present and appreciative of every moment. I can’t imagine not loving this stage with everything in me.

Kyrie Carter, you are the best thing to ever exist. I never want to forget these moments with you. Thank you for making me a mommy 🏹❣️

What’s one thing motherhood has taught you?🫀

Kyrie Carter, these first two months of life with you have been an absolute dream. 

While going through pregnancy, by biggest fear was postpartum. So many woman battle with identity loss, anxiety, depression, confusion, exhaustion, and so many more dark emotions, all while also experiencing the best times of their life. A roller coaster. This is all that’s talked about, and because it’s so common this is exactly what I was prepared to experience. 

The truth for me is motherhood hasn’t been any of those things. It hasn’t been hard and it hasn’t put me in a depressive state. Our days feel natural, they flow, I don’t feel sad or miss what life used to be. I haven’t had days behind the camera where I’m sitting in puddles of my own tears, where I’m broken down and feeling lost. & thankfully I was 1000% more tired during pregnancy than I am now. 

Because I had fear of what my postpartum experience would be like, I went into motherhood making an agreement to myself that I would not strain myself. I would stay open minded and release all pressure and or expectations I may have once had. That being said, there are many traditional things I thought I’d do, that I truly wanted to do, but one by one quickly decided not to as they seemed they may potentially add unnecessary discomfort and or stress. This was so big for me because I knew I could not be the best momma to Ky if mentally I was struggling.

Two months in and I’m standing so proudly in this mindset and full blown graceful state of motherhood. We all beautifully live in our own truth. As of now, this is mine. 💭❣️

Week full of firsts ❣️🕊️

Little Ky is one week shy of being 4 months old, meaning I have been a mom for almost 4 months now.

Struggles I’m facing:
Separation anxiety, I cannot be away from Kyrie for very long
Feeling fully confident in my body again (!!!!!)

The highs I’m praising:
Ky sleeps through the night (since 1 month old)
We talk all day & have so much fun together 
The first thing I see every morning is Ky smiling at me
Ky is just like his mommy & can sleep anywhere, anytime, no matter the noise level 👼🏽
Watching him learn new things & realize he has hands + feet and what he can do with them has been so cute 
He looks just like his daddy and even sleeps like him too 

Overall I was made to be Kyrie’s mother, we’re a perfect match. I feel so proud of both myself and Andre for the way we navigate parenthood - we can see it in Ky’s eyes everyday just how much he loves us and how happy he is. Children really are such a beautiful blessing. Thank you God ☁️🕊️❣️
